english:
  title: Record of the Shrine of Park, Lord of the Realm
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There was a gentleman of the Yuan court, Park, whose official title was Grand Master of Ceremonials and Superintendent of All Artisans' Offices of the Great Capital. For the sake of his ancestors, he erected a stele commemorating the restoration of Sinbok Temple, and had portraits painted of his parents, which he enshrined in a chapel to express his reverence for those long departed. Yet he chose not to keep these in his home, but rather at the temple itself—for he wished to secure for his ancestors the blessings of the hidden realm in perpetuity.

    The gentleman said to me: "I have long heard the learned say that to serve the living with propriety, to bury the dead with propriety, and to offer sacrifice with propriety—this is filial piety. But I, having left my parents in childhood and taken office in distant lands, knew not the evening inquiry nor morning attendance, nor asked after their tastes and comforts. Thus I have fallen short in serving them in life. When my parents passed, I was bound to the palace and could not rush to their side or tend to their burial rites. And now, with family temples fallen into disuse and beliefs in seeking karmic merit taking their place, even our ancestral rites remain incomplete. Each time I ponder this, my heart breaks with sorrow. Though I wish to make amends, I have no sons to carry on, and I fear that my ancestors' worship may not endure. Therefore have I built this chapel and granted to it twelve plots of land in my village, whose yearly harvest shall forever provide for seasonal offerings, that my brothers and descendants never forget. I ask you to set this down in writing."

    Regarding Park's deeds, I have already recorded them in detail upon the stone at Sinbok Temple, so I shall not repeat them here. Rather, I preserve his words, and note the boundaries of the granted lands on the reverse of this stone. And I make this proclamation to Park's brothers and descendants: "Brothers share the same vital essence. The sons of brothers are as your own sons. Therefore, regard Park as a father. Can any disregard a father's words? All who serve their parents as Park has served is indeed filial. Train your children and grandchildren that they forget not his words nor abandon his deeds. Then this chapel shall not stand in vain, and the hearts of all your descendants shall naturally bloom with filial devotion and reverence."

    Recorded on the fifteenth day of the first moon in the sixth year of Zhizheng, in the year of the Male Dog.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''Record of Filial Piety'' references the Analects: to serve living parents with propriety, bury them with propriety, and sacrifice to them with propriety constitutes filial piety.'
    - '''Evening inquiry and morning attendance'' refers to the Confucian ideal of visiting parents in the morning and evening to tend to their needs.'
    - The 'hidden realm' (myeong-bok) refers to blessings accrued through merit-making and Buddhist practices that benefit the deceased in the afterlife.
    - The year of the Male Dog corresponds to 1346 CE in the Yuan Dynasty period.
